definition.value: An organic compound having at least one hydroxy group attached to a carbon atom.
Alkenols; the term refers specifically to vinylic alcohols, which have the structure HOCR'=CR2. Enols are tautomeric with aldehydes (R' = H) or ketones (R' =/= H).
Alk-1-yn-1-ols, RC#COH; tautomeric with ketenes RCH=C=O.
A pentonic acid resulting from the formal oxidation of the aldehyde group of aldehydo-xylose to the corresponding carboxylic acid.

An indolizidine alkaloid that is  galanthan substituted by analpha-hydroxy group at position 1 and a methylenedioxy group across position 9 and 10. An alkaloid commonly found in the members of the family amaryllidaceae.
Any organic molecule that consists of atoms connected in the form of a ring.

A heterocyclic compound formally derived from an arene by replacement of one or more methine (-C=) and/or vinylene (-CH=CH-) groups by trivalent or divalent heteroatoms, respectively, in such a way as to maintain the continuous pi-electron system characteristic of aromatic systems and a number of out-of-plane pi-electrons corresponding to the Hueckel rule (4n+2).
A member of the class of anthracenes that is  9,10-dihydroanthracene carrying an oxo group at C-9.
Conjugated protein is a protein that contains a non-peptide component, usually in stoichiometric proportion.
An N-glycosyl compound that has both a nucleobase, normally adenine, guanine, xanthine, thymine, cytosine or uracil, and either a ribose or deoxyribose as functional parents.

A macromolecule is a molecule of high relative molecular mass, the structure of which essentially comprises the multiple repetition of units derived, actually or conceptually, from molecules of low relative molecular mass.
A hexonic acid derivative that is formally obtained from gulonic acid.
A hexonic acid derivative that is formally obtained from altronic acid.
An antibiotic isolated from various Streptomyces species. It interferes with protein and DNA synthesis by inhibiting peptidyl transferase or the 80S ribosome system.
A pentonic acid derivative that is formally obtained from arabinonic acid.
A pentonic acid derivative that is formally obtained from a ribonic acid.
A pentonic acid derivative that is formally obtained from xylonic acid.
A monocyclic aromatic hydrocarbon.
A polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon.
Organic aromatic compounds having one or more hydroxy groups attached to a benzene or other arene ring.
Any alcohol in which the alcoholic hydroxy group is attached to a carbon which is itself bonded to an aromatic ring.
Any aldehyde in which the carbonyl group is attached to an aromatic moiety.
An amino acid whose structure includes an aromatic ring.
Any primary alcohol in which the alcoholic hydroxy group is attached to a carbon which is itself bonded to an aromatic ring.
Any carboxylic acid in which the carboxy group is directly bonded to an aromatic ring.
An amino compound in which the amino group is linked directly to an aromatic system.
A dibenzoazepine that is 5H-dibenzo[b,f]azepine carrying a carbamoyl substituent at the azepine nitrogen, used as an anticonvulsant.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of glyceric acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A hexaric acid derivative that is formally obtained from allaric acid.
A hexanic acid derivative that is formally obtained from idaric acid.
A hexaric acid derivative that is formally obtained from mannaric acid.
